title: Don't use Paillier-tric during issuing
message:
Don't use Paillier-tric during issuing

There is no use, because:
- We are linkable anyway through the signature of the KSS;
- If we did use the Paillier-tric, then the KSS's signature
  would sign the Paillier-encrypted response, but then we can't
  be sure that this ciphertext is indeed an encryption of the
  (unsigned) plaintext response (which the client would have to
  provide separately).

title: Switched from SyncHttpClient to Http(s)URLConnection for the POSTs and GETs in the HttpClient
message:
Switched from SyncHttpClient to Http(s)URLConnection for the POSTs and GETs in the HttpClient

Although HttpsURLConnection is lower level than SyncHTTPClient, it is a better choice:

 * See http://android-developers.blogspot.nl/2011/09/androids-http-clients.html, an official blog post recommending using HttpURLConnection,
 * SyncHttpClient is based on Apache's org.apache.http.client.HttpClient which is deprecated in Android, as can be seen from its many @Deprecated annotations,
 * SyncHttpClient (or rather Apache's SSLSocketFactory) ignores the Subject Alt Name field in the X509 certificate presented by the server, while HttpsURLConnection respects this field. This is not only more convenient for us, but actually also as it should be according to the RFC.
 * HttpsURLConnection should also allow configuring the ciphers that the client accepts (but I have not yet done this).

title: Refactoring: total separation between UI code and network/issuing code
message:
Refactoring: total separation between UI code and network/issuing code

All network and issuing code now runs on its own separate thread, and this thread is managed by the EnrollClient class. This class offers a single method, EnrollClient.enroll(), that gets the process going, and when done it reports back to the calling thread via a specified Handler.

The following has also changed:
* we now connect the MNO after we've made contact with the passport, instead of before
* we no longer connect to the government server; for now we just issue the credential directly

Get self enrolling to work with the new scuba and the stock JMRTD

When talking to the passport, JRMTD uses a MAC called ISO9797Alg3Mac that should be provided by Bouncycastle, but for some reason isn't, so we let Spongycastle provide it. (It is known that android comes with a broken/incomplete version of Bouncycastle; probably this is the cause of the problem.)

title: Dirty hack: detect card loss
message:
Dirty hack: detect card loss

We work around the fact that Android doesn't send notifications for lost cards.
Instead, we send a vacuous command to test whether the card is still present.
But, the vacuous command is protocol specific, so this makes the cardproxy too
dependent on the actual protocol in use.

title: First changes to make the cardproxy less smart.
message:
First changes to make the cardproxy less smart.

The refactoring on the irma webservice has sparkled the realization that a too smart cardproxy app makes for a lot of duplicate work at the webservice and cardproxy app. The changes in this commit work towards an approach where the javascript in the browser is the "master" and the cardproxy app behaves more like a "dumb" cardreader. This has the additional advantage that it makes the user experience more consistent across smartcard reader devices.

Do note however that the current version is incomplete and mostly untested. I.e., it is work in progress.
